step.context:
%text
\underline\text{A theoretical question}
If \[ f(x) = \frac{1}{(x-a)^2}\], then \underline\text{what is $f(x) + f'(x)?$}
%

step.reason:
%text
On seeing \[ \frac{x-4}{(x-2)^3} \], we noticed that  

%
\begin{align}
(x-4) - (x-2) &= -2 \\
\text{and }\frac{d}{dx}\frac{1}{(x-2)^2} &= \frac{-2}{(x-2)^3} 
\end{align} 

%text


So, that is two ways of getting a $-2$. 
Seems to be \underline\text{more than a coincidence}.

And hence, \underline\text{we wondered} what $f(x) + f'(x)$ 
would be if $f(x) = \frac{1}{(x-a)^2}$
%
\begin{align}
f(x)  = \frac{1}{(x-a)^2} &\implies f'(x) = \frac{-2}{(x-a)^3} \\
\therefore f(x) + f'(x) &= \frac{1}{(x-a)^2} -\frac{2}{(x-a)^3} \\
&= \frac{x-(a+2)}{(x-a)^3}
\end{align}

\begin{align}
\frac{x-4}{(x-2)^3} = \frac{(x-2) - 2}{(x-2)^3} &= \frac{1}{(x-2)^2}-\frac{2}{(x-2)^3}\\
\therefore \int e^x\frac{x-4}{(x-2)^3}dx  &= \int e^x [f(x) + f'(x)]\cdot dx \\
\text{where }f(x) &= \frac{1}{(x-2)^2} \\
\therefore I = e^x\cdot f(x) + C &= \frac{e^x}{(x-2)^2} + C
\end{align}
